          "body": "Chronicles 1–9 is a genealogical prologue that establishes Israel's identity before the narrative begins. Within that prologue, Levi receives more attention than any other tribe — 81 verses in chapter 6 alone, compared to far briefer treatments of Judah (chapters 2–4) and Benjamin (chapter 8). The disproportion is the Chronicler's argument. He is writing for the post-exilic community (probably late fifth or early fourth century BC) that has returned from Babylon to rebuild the temple and its worship. The community's existential questions are: Is our priesthood legitimate? Do our temple singers hold valid Levitical credentials? Do we have any claim to the cities the Torah promised our tribe? Chapter 6 answers all three with the same instrument: genealogy as legal title. The chapter is not religious history for its own sake; it is a constitutional document for a community rebuilding its worship identity."
