          "body": "Verses 1–15 trace the high-priestly succession from Aaron through twenty-two generations to Jehozadak, who went into exile in 586 BC. The genealogy is not complete — modern scholarship identifies gaps, and some names appear to be telescoped — but the Chronicler's point is not exhaustiveness but unbrokenness. The line runs through Phinehas (who received the covenant of a perpetual priesthood, Numbers 25:13), through Zadok (David's loyalist high priest who anointed Solomon, 1 Kings 1:39), through Hilkiah (who discovered the law book under Josiah, 2 Kings 22:8), to Jehozadak. The single historical note embedded in the list — 'it was he who served as the priest in the house which Solomon built in Jerusalem' (v. 10) — marks the apex of the whole sweep. Then v. 15 delivers the catastrophe without softening: the LORD carried Judah away by Nebuchadnezzar's hand. But Jehozadak's son Jeshua ben Jehozadak returned from Babylon with Zerubbabel (Ezra 2:2; 3:2). The genealogy traverses the exile intact. Post-exilic Aaronic priests are holding an unbroken commission."
