          "body": "One of the chapter's most striking moments is easily missed: verse 28 places Samuel's sons Joel and Abijah in the Kohathite genealogy of Elkanah, and verses 33–38 trace Heman the singer back through Samuel himself (v. 33). Samuel is nowhere in the Aaronic line — he was not a priest. But he was a Levite, specifically a Kohathite through Elkanah. The Chronicler deliberately includes Samuel in the Levitical register (a point reinforced in 1 Chronicles 9:22, where Samuel and David together are credited with establishing gatekeepers). This serves multiple purposes. It legitimizes Samuel's cultic functions (offering sacrifice, 1 Samuel 7:9; 9:13) as Levitical rather than priestly — a distinction the Chronicler is at pains to maintain elsewhere. It also connects the greatest judge-prophet of the pre-monarchic era directly to the First Temple singing guilds through his grandson Heman. The Davidic worship program was not invented from scratch; it grew from Samuel's own lineage."
